ğŸ˜ PHP Conditional Statements
A conditional statement allows you to execute different blocks of code depending on whether a condition is true or false.
=======================================================================================================================
1. The if Statement
The simplest conditional: executes code if the condition is true.

<?php
$age = 20;

if ($age >= 18) {
    echo "You are an adult.";
}
?>
---------------------
ğŸ‘‰ Output:
You are an adult.

*********************************************************************************************

2. The if...else Statement
Runs one block if the condition is true, another if false.

<?php
$age = 16;

if ($age >= 18) {
    echo "You can vote.";
} else {
    echo "You cannot vote yet.";
}
?>
---------------------
ğŸ‘‰ Output:
You cannot vote yet.


*********************************************************************************************

3. The if...elseif...else Statement

Used when you have multiple conditions.

<?php
$marks = 75;

if ($marks >= 90) {
    echo "Grade: A+";
} elseif ($marks >= 75) {
    echo "Grade: A";
} elseif ($marks >= 50) {
    echo "Grade: B";
} else {
    echo "Grade: F";
}
?>
------------------------------
ğŸ‘‰ Output:
Grade: A

*********************************************************************************************

4. The Ternary Operator (?:)

Shorthand for simple if...else.

<?php
$age = 18;
$message = ($age >= 18) ? "Adult" : "Minor";
echo $message;
?>
---------------------------------
ğŸ‘‰ Output:
Adult


*********************************************************************************************

5. Null Coalescing Operator (??)

Checks if a variable exists/is not null.

<?php
$username = $_GET['user'] ?? "Guest";
echo "Hello, $username!";
?>


ğŸ‘‰ If ?user=John in URL â†’ Output:
Hello, John!


ğŸ‘‰ If no query â†’ Output:
Hello, Guest!


*********************************************************************************************

6. The switch Statement

Best when youâ€™re checking one variable against many values.

<?php
$day = "Tue";

switch ($day) {
    case "Mon":
        echo "Start of the week!";
        break;
    case "Tue":
        echo "Second day!";
        break;
    case "Fri":
        echo "Weekend is near!";
        break;
    default:
        echo "Just another day.";
}
?>

-------------------------
ğŸ‘‰ Output:
Second day!



*********************************************************************************************

7. Nested if Statements

One if inside another.

<?php
$age = 25;
$citizen = true;

if ($age >= 18) {
    if ($citizen) {
        echo "You are eligible to vote.";
    } else {
        echo "You must be a citizen to vote.";
    }
} else {
    echo "You are too young to vote.";
}
?>



*********************************************************************************************

9. Switch with Multiple Cases (Fall-through)

You can group cases together.

<?php
$day = "Sat";

switch ($day) {
    case "Sat":
    case "Sun":
        echo "Weekend!";
        break;
    default:
        echo "Weekday!";
}
?>

ğŸ‘‰ Output:
Weekend!


*********************************************************************************************

10. Advanced: Match Expression (PHP 8+)
Similar to switch but more concise and strict comparison.

<?php
$day = "Mon";

$message = match($day) {
    "Mon" => "Start of the week!",
    "Fri" => "Almost weekend!",
    "Sat", "Sun" => "Weekend!",
    default => "Midweek day.",
};

echo $message;
?>


ğŸ‘‰ Output:
Start of the week!
